The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Sports | Briefs
                                                                                                                                                         Modi in trouble again
    Jaipur: The Rajasthan High Court Friday issued Lalit Modi a notice asking why his bail should not be cancelled in a cheating case as he did not take due permission from the court before leaving India.
    Justice S.P. Pathak issued the notice after hearing a petition filed by NGO Nagrik Morcha, which moved the application on April 22. The court asked Modi to explain his reason for leaving India without permission.  Cup meeting
    Calcutta: The 2011 World Cup organising committee is to be revamped on Tuesday when it meets at the BCCI headquarters in Mumbai, its first sitting since the ICC snatched away hosting rights of the mega event from Pakistan.   Imran call
    Dubai: Former Pakistan captain Imran Khan said Friday that ICC should swap the 2011 and 2015 World Cup venues, rather than deprive Pakistan of its matches in the 2011 tournament.
    Pepe banned
    Madrid: Real Madrid defender Pepe has been banned for 10 games for lashing out at two Getafe players in a Spanish league match. 
    Indians out
    New Delhi: Prakash Amritraj went down fighting in the semi-finals 7-6 (7-5), 3-6, 4-6 to American John Isner while Harsh Mankad and his Austrian partner Martin Fischer lost 7-6 (7-4), 4-6, 5-10 to Japanese-Thai pair of Go Soeda and Danai Udomchoke at the ATP Challenger event in Tallahassee, US putting an end to the Indian challenge.
    Yuki in final
    New Delhi: Yuki Bhambri stormed into the singles final of the $15,000 ITF Futures event defeating Japanese qualifier Masato Hatanaka 6-4, 6-4 Friday. He will now fight it with compatriot Vishnu Vardhan for his first title on men rsquo;s circuit.
